hydroponic conditions--

00:40:04.190 --> 00:40:04.870
NANCY SINGLETON HACHISU:
Yeah, that's a big thing now.

00:40:04.870 --> 00:40:07.661
AUDIENCE: So they are very
pretty, and they're very sweet.

00:40:07.661 --> 00:40:09.160
They just don't
have depth of flavor

00:40:09.160 --> 00:40:10.940
that we have here in
the States, actually.

00:40:10.940 --> 00:40:12.360
NANCY SINGLETON HACHISU:
Tokyo has bad vegetables.

00:40:12.360 --> 00:40:14.693
AUDIENCE: Yeah, I found the
vegetables better in the US.

00:40:14.693 --> 00:40:16.280
Even though they
don't look as nice.

00:40:16.280 --> 00:40:18.090
NANCY SINGLETON HACHISU: I think
the chef's really concentrate

00:40:18.090 --> 00:40:20.130
on-- they're very
good about fish.

00:40:20.130 --> 00:40:22.410
So you can get good fish
pretty much anywhere,

00:40:22.410 --> 00:40:24.680
but it's really hard for
me to eat in Tokyo now,

00:40:24.680 --> 00:40:26.840
because I'm really
into vegetables,

00:40:26.840 --> 00:40:29.962
and it's like a
zero on the plate.

00:40:29.962 --> 00:40:30.850
AUDIENCE: Hello.

00:40:30.850 --> 00:40:33.826
How difficult is the soy sauce
process, or making soy sauce?

00:40:33.826 --> 00:40:35.534
NANCY SINGLETON HACHISU:
Yeah, soy sauce.

00:40:39.420 --> 00:40:44.740
We so far have a small
soy sauce place in Nagano

00:40:44.740 --> 00:40:48.090
who takes my friend
who grows the beans,

00:40:48.090 --> 00:40:51.290
and he grows the wheat.

00:40:51.290 --> 00:40:57.169
And then they inoculate it
with-- they put the koji in,

00:40:57.169 --> 00:40:59.210
and then we rush up with
air, we put the salt on.

00:40:59.210 --> 00:41:05.810
But basically, you mix
in steamed soybeans

00:41:05.810 --> 00:41:10.460
with wheat that's been
inoculated with koji,

00:41:10.460 --> 00:41:12.940
and you add salt and water.

00:41:12.940 --> 00:41:18.870
And you stick it in a
barrel of some kind,

00:41:18.870 --> 00:41:23.850
and let it sit for
a year to two years.

00:41:23.850 --> 00:41:24.940
I'm making fish sauce now.

00:41:24.940 --> 00:41:25.440
We'll see.

00:41:25.440 --> 00:41:27.270
It will take a year and a half.

00:41:27.270 --> 00:41:30.630
Put the salt-- 17%
salt-- with mashed up,

00:41:30.630 --> 00:41:32.930
chopped up fish in a pot.

00:41:32.930 --> 00:41:35.800
Wait a year and a half.

00:41:35.800 --> 00:41:36.430
We'll see.

00:41:36.430 --> 00:41:39.930
That Japanese fish sauce, you
should start looking for that.

00:41:39.930 --> 00:41:44.090
It's really hard to find here,
but it is really, really,

00:41:44.090 --> 00:41:44.960
really good.

00:41:44.960 --> 00:41:47.310
You tasted some at
my house, right?

00:41:47.310 --> 00:41:51.770
I have some macro fish sauce
from the Stubborn Mother

00:41:51.770 --> 00:41:54.030
in the Wajima market.

00:41:54.030 --> 00:41:55.950
No label, it's a
[? pet ?] bottle.

00:41:55.950 --> 00:41:59.320
And it is just so good.

00:41:59.320 --> 00:42:01.610
But she puts not just
guts and heads in.

00:42:01.610 --> 00:42:04.290
She puts in the meat
of the fish too.

00:42:04.290 --> 00:42:09.060
Helps it be sweeter.

00:42:09.060 --> 00:42:11.260
But it kicks ass on
all other fish sauces.

00:42:11.260 --> 00:42:13.670
Totally.

00:42:13.670 --> 00:42:15.360
LIV WU: Yes, Peter.

00:42:15.360 --> 00:42:17.776
NANCY SINGLETON HACHISU: Um,
there's three names actually.

00:42:17.776 --> 00:42:21.000
The northern place,
Akita, calls it Shottsuru,

00:42:21.000 --> 00:42:22.570
and it's usually
made from sandfish

00:42:22.570 --> 00:42:26.790
or sometimes squid or sardines.

00:42:26.790 --> 00:42:31.510
And then the
Ishikawa prefecture,

00:42:31.510 --> 00:42:33.290
which is where the
Noto Peninsula is,

00:42:33.290 --> 00:42:36.050
they call it Ishiri or Ishiru.

00:42:36.050 --> 00:42:39.470
And they have-- I mean, the
whole culture down there

00:42:39.470 --> 00:42:41.470
is all about that.

00:42:41.470 --> 00:42:45.730
And that's what really
was fascinating for me.

00:42:45.730 --> 00:42:46.980
My husband had used it before.

00:42:46.980 --> 00:42:49.280
I always had it at home,
and I used it sometimes.

00:42:49.280 --> 00:42:50.738
And I put a little
bit in the book.

00:42:50.738 --> 00:42:53.510
But once I went to the
maker, and I talked to them,

00:42:53.510 --> 00:42:56.360
and all these different
ways to use it.

00:42:56.360 --> 00:42:58.600
They call it [? kakshaji, ?]
just a little

00:42:58.600 --> 00:42:59.780
bit it of hidden taste.

00:42:59.780 --> 00:43:02.770
So I put it in, just choo.

00:43:02.770 --> 00:43:05.030
You don't want to
taste it so much.

00:43:05.030 --> 00:43:07.390
It's really good with
like a thin pickly thing.

00:43:07.390 --> 00:43:11.090
And I put it in
Western daubes or stew.

00:43:11.090 --> 00:43:17.180
Or I put it in fried rice,
just choo, a little bit.

00:43:17.180 --> 00:43:18.390
LIV WU: The secret umami hit.

00:43:18.390 --> 00:43:22.420
NANCY SINGLETON HACHISU:
So it's a hidden taste.

00:43:22.420 --> 00:43:24.320
All these areas are big
on the hidden taste.

00:43:24.320 --> 00:43:27.944
Like, Katsubishi area, they
put katsuobushi on everything.

00:43:27.944 --> 00:43:28.860
It's not hidden taste.

00:43:28.860 --> 00:43:30.550
It's like every single thing.

00:43:30.550 --> 00:43:33.990
They put it on the raw
egg on rice and soy sauce,

00:43:33.990 --> 00:43:36.750
katsuobushi too.

00:43:36.750 --> 00:43:40.240
The vinegar people, they
put it in everything.

00:43:40.240 --> 00:43:42.186
Just as a choo.

00:43:42.186 --> 00:43:43.810
LIV WU: So I'm coming
to the conclusion

00:43:43.810 --> 00:43:49.730
that one of the foundational
secrets of cooking

00:43:49.730 --> 00:43:53.820
and controlling flavor is
dealing with fermentation.

00:43:53.820 --> 00:43:55.430
Or, if you want to
put it another way,

00:43:55.430 --> 00:43:58.310
is controlling rot.

00:43:58.310 --> 00:43:59.980
And that really is.

00:43:59.980 --> 00:44:01.730
NANCY SINGLETON HACHISU:
Sandor Katz said,

00:44:01.730 --> 00:44:03.510
don't be afraid of the mold.

00:44:03.510 --> 00:44:06.486
So sometimes with my pickles I
got something going on on them,

00:44:06.486 --> 00:44:08.410
and I just take it off.

00:44:08.410 --> 00:44:11.990
Same thing when I do
sauerkraut-- and also,

00:44:11.990 --> 00:44:14.890
not being afraid of
getting rid of the plastic.

00:44:14.890 --> 00:44:17.650
So I always made my
sauerkraut in a plastic bag.

00:44:17.650 --> 00:44:20.860
We have pickling bags, they're
food-grade pickling bags.

00:44:20.860 --> 00:44:24.830
But I'm moving on
to all of my-- I

00:44:24.830 --> 00:44:26.770
have this cabbage ready
to go before I left,

00:44:26.770 --> 00:44:29.020
and I didn't have time to do
it, so I stick it in the fridge.

00:44:29.020 --> 00:44:29.715
Hopefully, I can try it.

00:44:29.715 --> 00:44:31.450
But I'm going to try the
sauerkraut without the pickling

00:44:31.450 --> 00:44:32.020
bag.

00:44:32.020 --> 00:44:34.000
But just put it in
a wooden barrel,

00:44:34.000 --> 00:44:38.400
and put some muslin on top.

00:44:38.400 --> 00:44:42.430
And I think the
plastic promotes mold.

00:44:42.430 --> 00:44:45.165
I'm very unscientific
about my pickling.

00:44:47.955 --> 00:44:49.810
AUDIENCE: What's the
deal about natto?

00:44:49.810 --> 00:44:51.268
NANCY SINGLETON
HACHISU: Oh, natto?

00:44:51.268 --> 00:44:52.780
Good natto is really good.

00:44:52.780 --> 00:44:55.880
I've made it-- I
had an experiment,

00:44:55.880 --> 00:45:03.040
and I made it-- natto naturally
ferments in the rice straw.

00:45:03.040 --> 00:45:06.490
And I tried it
within the rice straw

00:45:06.490 --> 00:45:12.120
or inoculating it with the
natto-kin, the natto powder

00:45:12.120 --> 00:45:12.630
spores.

00:45:12.630 --> 00:45:18.310
Or you can take some natto
slime and add some warm water

00:45:18.310 --> 00:45:19.970
and harvest.

00:45:19.970 --> 00:45:23.620
So, I got it from the Yamaki--
my people, got some very natto

00:45:23.620 --> 00:45:28.682
and I made a little solution,
inoculated the beans with that.

00:45:28.682 --> 00:45:30.140
They all tasted
good, but the thing

00:45:30.140 --> 00:45:33.930
is I should have been
more scientific about it.

00:45:33.930 --> 00:45:36.440
I should have put it in a
controlled heat environment.

00:45:36.440 --> 00:45:39.010
It was a very cool few
days in the summer.

00:45:39.010 --> 00:45:40.960
And so I decided I'd
put it in the car.

00:45:40.960 --> 00:45:43.060
And then one day I
woke up in the morning.

00:45:43.060 --> 00:45:45.490
It was like the heat
arc had gone way up.

00:45:45.490 --> 00:45:47.400
But it was delicious.

00:45:47.400 --> 00:45:52.230
The best one was the
one in the straw.

00:45:52.230 --> 00:45:54.340
They weren't slimy,
but they tasted good.

00:45:54.340 --> 00:45:56.350
And so, I still have
to get back into it.

00:45:56.350 --> 00:45:58.475
But there's a method where
you put it in a big hole

00:45:58.475 --> 00:46:01.214
in the ground and
you put it in straw

00:46:01.214 --> 00:46:03.630
in a big hole in the ground,
and you pour hot water on it.

00:46:03.630 --> 00:46:04.796
Then you pack it with earth.

00:46:04.796 --> 00:46:06.230
I'm going to do that next.

00:46:06.230 --> 00:46:09.340
My friend described it.

00:46:09.340 --> 00:46:10.770
Yeah, good natto is really good.

00:46:10.770 --> 00:46:13.020
But it should be good natto.

00:46:13.020 --> 00:46:15.590
Can't find good natto very
much in Japan anymore.

00:46:15.590 --> 00:46:20.230
It's all-- none of it's
organic, except for our friends.

00:46:20.230 --> 00:46:22.500
Not much of it.

